[center][size=5][color=#D3BCFD][b]SimpleIME — User Guide[/b][/color][/size][/center]

[line]

[size=4][color=#D3BCFD][b]Tool Window[/b][/color][/size]

Press [b]F2[/b] (default) to open/close the Tool Window. You can reassign this shortcut in Settings.

[list]
[*][b]Pin[/b] — keeps the window always visible; it collapses to a compact language bar you can move to any corner.
[*][b]Enable / Disable Mod[/b] — temporarily releases keyboard control without uninstalling. Use this when another mod needs exclusive input.
[/list]

If the window goes off-screen after a resolution change, delete the [i][Window][ToolWindow##SimpleIME][/i] section from [i]imgui.ini[/i] in the game's interface folder (or delete the whole file). MO2 users: check the overwrite folder.

[line]

[size=4][color=#D3BCFD][b]Settings Reference[/b][/color][/size]

[list]
[*][b]enable-tsf[/b] — Strongly recommended. Uses the modern Text Services Framework for IME integration. Disable only if your OS is very old or TSF has been manually turned off. IMM32 fallback exists but is not reliable for modern input methods.
[*][b]keep_ime_open[/b] — Keeps the IME active even when no text field is focused. Useful for mods whose input fields support Unicode but do not call [i]AllowTextInput[/i] correctly.
[*][b]IME window position policy[/b] — Controls where the candidate/composition window appears. Options: Follow Caret (default, tracks GFxMovieView caret), Follow Cursor (tracks mouse cursor), None (fixed position). Set to [i]Follow Cursor[/i] or [i]None[/i] if your mod uses custom rendering like ImGui.
[/list]

[line]

[size=4][color=#D3BCFD][b]IME Actions & Shortcuts[/b][/color][/size]

All IME actions (composition, candidate selection) and shortcuts (e.g. [b]Ctrl+Space[/b] to switch input mode) work exactly as in any other Windows application. Refer to your input method's own documentation for the full shortcut list.

[line]

[size=4][color=#D3BCFD][b]Recommended: Microsoft IME[/b][/color][/size]

SimpleIME is primarily developed and tested against Microsoft's built-in input methods (Microsoft Pinyin, Microsoft Japanese IME). Third-party IMEs (iFly, Sogou, Baidu, etc.) may not fully conform to the TSF specification, which can cause missing features or incorrect behavior. I may add targeted workarounds over time, but full third-party IME support is not guaranteed.

[line]

[size=4][color=#D3BCFD][b]Event Interception[/b][/color][/size]

[size=3][b]Interception while IME is active[/b][/size]

While SimpleIME is active and a [color=#D3BCFD]valid input method[/color] is present, it intercepts all keyboard input events to prevent underlying menus from receiving raw character or key input. Pure character input is compensated via [i]WM_CHAR[/i] messages on the IME thread (e.g., typing in English mode with a CJK input method active). This is intentional — you generally do not want the underlying menu acting on raw keystrokes during IME composition.

[size=3][b]Interception while the Settings window is open[/b][/size]

When the SimpleIME settings window is opened from the language bar, it blocks all underlying menus from receiving any input. Think of it as just another menu — no different in nature from the inventory, map, or container menus.

[line]

[size=4][color=#D3BCFD][b]Known Issues[/b][/color][/size]

[list]
[*][b]Win+Shift+S during composition[/b] — Pressing the Snipping Tool shortcut while a CJK composition is active and switching windows at exactly the right moment can cause a crash. Root cause is under investigation.
[*][b]iFly IME[/b] — English/Chinese mode switch is not detected because iFly does not send a conversion-mode change message.
[/list]
